{
  "id": "019cfc26-8535-7003-aaab-6d7ecae53617",
  "content": "## SAM2 OOM on 4K footage with 6GB VRAM (2025-11-01 test run)\n\n### Problem\nSAM2's `init_state(video_path=frame_dir)` loads ALL extracted JPEG frames into memory at initialization. With 4K footage (3840x2160) from the DJI Action 4, a single clip (DJI_20251101111232_0053_D) produced 2221 frames. The process was OOM-killed during frame loading despite `offload_video_to_cpu=True`.\n\nThe frame loading alone at 4K resolution (~24MB per uncompressed frame) requires ~53GB RAM for 2221 frames, far exceeding available system memory.\n\n### Observed behavior\n```\nClip DJI_20251101111232_0053_D: 2221 frames extracted, 3 subject(s) to track\nframe loading (JPEG):   2%|▏         | 40/2221 [00:04<03:47,  9.60it/s]\nKilled\n```\nExit code 137 (SIGKILL from OOM killer).\n\n### Potential fixes (not yet implemented)\n1. **Downscale frames before SAM2 init** — extract frames at 1080p or 720p instead of native 4K. SAM2 internally resizes to 1024px anyway, so full 4K extraction wastes memory. Add `-vf scale=1280:-1` to the `extract_frames_to_dir` ffmpeg call in script 03.\n2. **Use SAM2's `async_loading_frames=True`** — if supported by this version, loads frames lazily instead of all at once.\n3. **Process clips in segments** — split long clips into shorter segments, track across segments with re-initialization.\n\nOption 1 is the simplest and most effective — matches Phase 1's keyframe extraction resolution (1280px wide) and eliminates the memory bottleneck entirely. The depth model (Phase 4) processes frames one at a time and handles 4K fine (~1.5GB VRAM).",
  "source_version": "mcp",
  "scope_id": "dorea",
  "workstream": "main",
